// Note: Mongolian uses "мянган" (nominative мянга) for thousand,
// "сая" for million, "тэрбум" for billion, "их наяд" for trillion.
// The forms _0MA1, _0M1 etc. might need careful adaptation based on Mongolian grammar if numbers combine with nouns in complex ways.
// For simplicity, using the base forms here.

_1MA1   m;jangG@    // мянга (one thousand - нэг мянга)
_0MA1   m;jangG@    // мянга (thousands of - мянган)
_0M1    m;jangG@    // мянга
_1MA2   saj;@       // сая
_0MA2   saj;@       // сая
_0M2    saj;@       // сая
_1MA3   t;erbʊm_    // тэрбум
_0MA3   t;erbʊm_    // тэрбум
_0M3    t;erbʊm_    // тэрбум
_1MA4   Ix naj;@d_  // их наяд
_0MA4   Ix naj;@d_  // их наяд
_0M4    Ix naj;@d_  // их наяд

// Decimal point related words
// Mongolian might use "таслал" (taslal) for comma/decimal point, or "цэг" (tseg) for point.
// "аравны" (aravni) - tenths, "зууны" (zuuni) - hundredths, "мянны" (myangiin) - thousandths
_dpt    t_AslAl_    // таслал (comma, also used for decimal point)
// For _dpt2, this is more complex as it depends on the number of decimal places.
// e.g., "аравны нэг" (aravni neg) - 0.1, "зууны тав" (zuuni tav) - 0.05
// A generic ending might not be straightforward.
// Let's use a placeholder or a common way to say "point" as in "three point one four"
_dpt    tsEg_       // цэг (point) - can be used like "гурван цэг нэг дөрөв" for 3.14
_dpt2   Ar@vnY_     // аравны (tenths - if the fraction ends like "X tenths") - this is a guess

